&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Red Legged Partridge is a really great game bird from a culinary point of view. Plump, juicy and a perfect one portion size, these birds cook in less than 20 minutes and are mild flavoured. As with all our birds, Harwood Game partridges are hand selected to be as shot free as possible.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Cooking tips:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Try poaching the Partridge in a rosemary infused chicken stock for 5 minutes, then brush the birds in olive oil, season with sea salt and pepper, push rosemary up its backside and roast for 10 to 12 minutes at 200&amp;deg;C! Rest for 6 or 7 minutes in a warm place before serving.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We love chestnuts with Partridge, also wild mushrooms, sherry and the odd English truffle!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Pheasant is the staple of the British sporting world. A generous sized bird, both cocks and hens are delicious. We select the best, shot on well managed sporting estates local to us in Berkshire. If you have specific requirements, please call us.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Cooking tips:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We very rarely roast whole Pheasants, but often cut them in half with game shears and sear and roast the halves in olive oil, garlic, white wine and lemon. Alternatively, use the thighs in casseroles and the breasts in place of chicken. Overcooking is the most common problem, leading to a dry meat. Pheasant should be moist, juicy and flavoursome. Use a temperature probe when roasting and bring the meat to 65&amp;deg;C, this will cook it without any danger of dryness.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The most common duck shot in the UK, Mallard make great eating and are readily available.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Cooking tips:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Ensure the bird is at room temperature before cooking. Remove the legs, leaving the crown, season and colour the crown in a pan with a splash of vegetable oil until golden, then roast in the pan until pink and juicy. Being a wild bird there will be size variations but we would think that 10 to 12 minutes at 160&amp;deg;C, then rested, will give you the required result.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The legs are best cooked slowly in goose fat &amp;agrave; la confit, then quickly roasted to finish. This has the added advantage of allowing you to keep back the legs for another meal. Breasts should be carved into long thin strips, not cut into thick chunks.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Much under-rated, the Wood Pigeon is increasingly in demand as an eating bird. Available as a whole bird or as breasts, they are simple to cook, available all year round and great value for money.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Cooking tips:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Pigeon should be cooked until pink, not fully brown. The meat has a delightful flavour, somewhere between beef and really good liver. Cook whole birds like a Grouse, otherwise pan fry seasoned breasts in butter for 90 seconds a side, then deglaze with sherry or balsamic vinegar, and rest for 3 minutes before carving. Try them in a warm salad with bacon and fried black pudding.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

