&lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 110%;&quot;&gt;A perfect trimmed fillet, similar in size to lamb, and the most finely grained and delicate of all the wild venison cuts.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 110%;&quot;&gt;&lt;em style=&quot;line-height: 110%;&quot;&gt;Cooking tips:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 110%;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;line-height: 110%;&quot;&gt;Very easy to portion, roast whole or cut into carpaccio, this is the finest venison there is.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;line-height: 110%;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;line-height: 110%;&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Great texture and terrific flavour.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Cooking tips:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Just as it is&amp;nbsp;&amp;ndash; the ultimate seasonal&amp;nbsp;amuse bouche.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Snipe is a phenomenally challenging game bird that is shot over damp, boggy patches of ground. Very small, but delicious, we get very few Snipe throughout the season, so if you see them available in our shop, snap them up!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Cooking tips:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Treat a Snipe like a miniature Woodcock, reducing cooking times by a third. Above all treat a Snipe with reverence, and ensure the breast meat is pink. If necessary, finish the legs in butter for a few moments in the oven. Snipe legs are perfect finger food but will be a little chewy (although delicious).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Roe loin is a lovely delicate piece of meat, with fine grain and a pale colour.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Cooking tips:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Ideal cut into medallions and seared in a pan, or gently roasted whole then carved, this mild and delicious cut could not be easier to use. A single loin will easily feed six.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Much under-rated, the Wood Pigeon is increasingly in demand as an eating bird. Available as a whole bird or as breasts, they are simple to cook, available all year round and great value for money.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Cooking tips:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Pigeon should be cooked until pink, not fully brown. The meat has a delightful flavour, somewhere between beef and really good liver. Cook whole birds like a Grouse, otherwise pan fry seasoned breasts in butter for 90 seconds a side, then deglaze with sherry or balsamic vinegar, and rest for 3 minutes before carving. Try them in a warm salad with bacon and fried black pudding.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A pav&amp;eacute; is a slab of beautiful meat taken from the individual haunch muscles, then trimmed of all sinew. This produces a lovely, fillet-like steak that is tender, yet has great texture and terrific flavour.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Cooking tips:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Roast, grill or barbecue, allow to rest and serve pink for best results.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A smaller version of the Roe shoulder, the Muntjac is perfect for two people.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Cooking tips:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Excellent slow braised or roasted, shoulder meat is well worked while the animal is alive and thus has a wonderful flavour. After braising in ale or red wine, the shoulder blade can be removed and the joint quickly glazed and roasted for absolutely stunning results.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Rabbit is another iconic animal. Thought to have been introduced to Britain by the Romans &amp;ndash; what did the Romans ever do for us?! These little animals have been a staple diet of the British for a couple of thousand years.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The meat is white, and from the opposite end of the colour spectrum from a Hare. Rabbits vary from young to old in size and tenderness, so we hand select the best of the bunch &amp;ndash; usually a first year Rabbit that has been rifle shot or ferreted.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Cooking tips:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We love boning and bashing out the back legs as an alternative to a chicken schnitzel, served with a parsnip and root vegetable coleslaw. Alternatively, braise the whole jointed Rabbit in Riesling, celery and mustard on a gentle heat until tender.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Rabbit loves to go with polenta, wild mushrooms, mashed potatoes (and with a naughty amount of butter!).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A pav&amp;eacute; is a slab of beautiful meat taken from the individual haunch muscles, then trimmed of all sinew. This produces a lovely, fillet-like steak that is tender, yet has great texture and terrific flavour.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The Roe Deer differs from the Fallow in texture and taste. The meat is very fine grained and slightly stronger than some of the other species. Our continental cousins prize it above all other meats.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Cooking tips:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Roast, grill or barbecue, allow to rest and serve pink for best results.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;

