&lt;p&gt;A pav&amp;eacute; is a slab of beautiful meat taken from the individual haunch muscles, then trimmed of all sinew. This produces a lovely, fillet-like steak that is tender, yet has great texture and terrific flavour.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The Sika is a remarkable deer. Although related to Red Deer, the meat is infinitely superior. Quite beefy, dark and yet mild in flavour, the Sika is highly prized for its eating qualities. A pav&amp;eacute; of Sika is a steak fit for a King.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Cooking tips:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Roast, grill or barbecue, allow to rest and serve pink for best results.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A whole shoulder of Roe deer can be prepared in a number of ways.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Cooking tips:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Excellent slow braised or roasted, this is a firm favourite at the Harwood Arms. Shoulder meat is well worked while the animal is alive and thus has a wonderful flavour. After braising in ale or red wine, quickly glaze and roast for absolutely stunning results.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A small but delicious double T-bone of Muntjac &amp;ndash; absolutely first class chops that melt in the mouth.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Cooking tips:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Try sprinkling with one of our deer seasonings after cooking. Best cooked on a griddle or a barbecue until evenly pink and juicy.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This is one of the most sought after cuts. Only ever from a two year or older deer, from which only 10 steaks can be taken. This cut is probably the favourite with our restaurant customers.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Cooking tips:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Season well and sear in a really hot pan, then roast for 6 to 7 minutes in a medium oven. After resting, sprinkle with juniper pepper and orange seasoning. Serve pink but cooked through for best results.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Red Grouse is one of Britain&amp;rsquo;s most iconic birds. Never reared and released, this is the wild bird of the heather hills and tastes of its environment. We hand select only the best birds from the finest Yorkshire moors, and carefully grade them to ensure minimum shot damage. We only supply &amp;lsquo;young&amp;rsquo; Grouse, which are less than a year old. Grouse are available from the &amp;lsquo;Glorious Twelfth&amp;rsquo; of August, but are in good supply a week later. Cooked as per our recipe, Grouse are both delicious and easy to prepare, as well as being hugely impressive.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Cooking tips:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Try poaching the Grouse from room temperature for 6 to 8 minutes in warm chicken stock at 80&amp;deg;C if you have a thermometer, if not, then keep the liquor just under a simmer. Remove and dry, then sear in a pan with a little vegetable oil and foaming butter, then roast in a medium oven until pink throughout (best not served really rare). We love cooking birds this way, since it avoids the classic problem of raw, jellied meat around the bones.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Superb with pumpkin, prunes cooked in tea, and the sauce finished with a wee dram of your favourite Scotch whisky.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Brown Hare is a magnificent animal, of great historic importance, that has been a royal animal in the past. Its value was so great in medieval times, that transportation or worse awaited the unlucky peasant who tried to pinch one!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Hares had a bad time in the post war era, but are now doing very well in many parts of the country, thanks to enlightened agricultural practises. We only supply hares from September to March, and insist on the animals being paunched in the field, not hung intact as was the old practise, which led to the rather stinky reputation that Hare sometimes has. If you want your Hare hung and smelly, call us!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Cooking tips:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Use the legs and shoulders of the Hare in a stew (jugged) or cook them in a pressure cooker with rosemary, garlic, tomatoes, olive oil and red wine to produce a rich rag&amp;ugrave;, which is amazing with fresh pappardelle pasta and parmesan.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Sear and roast the saddle, having seasoned it first, for 18 minutes at 200&amp;deg;C. Rest the saddle, then carve the fillets off the bone and serve for an amazing meal for two.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A whole boned out leg of this delicious venison, already butterflied, but with the thigh bone removed (bone will be included for your dog!).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Muntjac is denser grained than Chinese Water Deer, firmer in the mouth, and possibly a little stronger in flavour. Also Muntjac have less external fat than Chinese Water Deer.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Cooking tips:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This cut of venison will feed four to six people with ease and is perfect for roasting in the oven with a stuffing or for marinating and cooking on the barbecue. Delicious, mild. close grained meat that is very easy to cook to perfection.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

